    <text>
        <body>
            <pb n="1"/>
            <p rend="align(right)">
                <placeName>Montreal</placeName>
                <date>22d April 1861</date>
            </p>
            <p>
                <addressee>Rev Isaac Leeser</addressee>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Dear Sir—</p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">I should have<lb/> replied to your last favor earlier<lb/> but that
                I have had very little<lb/> leisure to do so. With reference<lb/> to the
                    <persName>Messrs Benjamins</persName> accounts<lb/> I have more than once
                called<lb/> their attention to their indebtedness<lb/> to you—as <persName>Mr
                    Joseph</persName> has also<lb/> done. I have no doubt <persName>Mr S.
                    B.</persName><lb/> will settle before he leaves for<lb/>
                <placeName>Europe</placeName>.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">I have taken no active<lb/> part in the commercial affairs<lb/> of
                our Calendar since I gave<lb/> you the former copies; but I</p>
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p><sic>I</sic> will send you a few copies<lb/> per earliest opportunity.
                    <persName>Mrs<lb/> Joseph</persName> goes soon I believe to<lb/>
                <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">I have commenced<lb/> a Biography of my late reverd<lb/> father
                    <add>זצ"ל</add>; but do not think<lb/> I shall publish it just yet—<lb/> I would
                gladly send it to the<lb/> Occident in its monthly form<lb/> but I was asked some
                time<lb/> back for a Biographical notice<lb/> by another Jewish paper and<lb/>
                <hi rend="underline">partially</hi> promised to give it<lb/> him. In any case I
                should be<lb/> glad to see it in your columns<lb/> if you deemed it suitable.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">I only live longer from<lb/> the unhappy hour of my beloved</p>
            <pb n="3"/>
            <p>parents death to realize more<lb/> and more the extent of his loss.<lb/> You knew but
                little very little<lb/> of him, but had you known his<lb/> deep learning which his
                meekness<lb/> but too much concealed—his<lb/> true piety, his manly upright<lb/>
                hearing and sterling worth—had<lb/> you ever seen him in the<lb/> domestic circle
                and observed<lb/> how all his children without<lb/> exception <sic>idolised</sic>
                him—and<lb/> how among the married ones<lb/> the tie was equally strong, you<lb/>
                could somewhat <sic>realise</sic> the bitter<lb/> grief of his children, and
                the<lb/> force of the blow which prostrated me<lb/> But through the mercy of
                the<lb/> Righteous Judge, I was not life<lb/> without much consolation form<lb/>
                above; his reputation, and the<lb/> numerous warm sympathizing</p>
            <pb n="4"/>
            <p>friends his widow &amp; children<lb/> found—the deep seated regret<lb/> which even
                now pervades his late<lb/> congregation who have mostly<lb/> grown up under him—and
                who<lb/> without exception respected and<lb/> loved him as a father, would not<lb/>
                be without consoling influence.<lb/> Never was Minister so universally<lb/> loved,
                and respected by the<lb/> sister congregations in
                <placeName>England</placeName>.<lb/> But Gods will be done <add>רוחי בגן
                עדן</add></p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">I presume you are aware<lb/> my brother <persName>Samuel</persName>
                has, in accordance<lb/> with my late fathers design &amp; wish<lb/> been appointed
                as assistant Hazan<lb/> for two years, and it is the unanimous<lb/> desire of the
                    <add>דה"ל</add> that he qualify himself<lb/> as a lecturer. He has
                matriculated<lb/> (after 1<hi rend="sup">st</hi> honors at Jews College) at the<lb/>
                London University for his degree of B. A.<lb/> More of this some other time. I
                must<lb/> now close.</p>
            <p rend="indent(11)">Yours truly</p>
            <p rend="indent(11)">
                <persName role="author">Abraham de Sola</persName>
            </p>
        </body>
